w-a.english: the [[ref|nominal particle|puingoa]] used before names and pronouns

w-aa.english:
1. and, and then
2. plural of tā
3. future time marker
w-aa.example: Ā te pō nei ka hui mātou.

w-aa-koorua.english: your [speaking to two people] (plural ā category possession)
w-aa-koorua.exampleTranslation: Where are your pens? (The pens belonging to you two.)
w-aa-koorua.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'kōrua' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takirua (dual second person pronoun).

w-aa-koutou.english: your [speaking to three or more people] (plural ā category possession)
w-aa-koutou.exampleTranslation: Where are your dogs? (The dogs belonging to you three or more people).
w-aa-koutou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'koutou' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitini (plural second person pronoun).

w-aa-maatou.english: our [mine and two or more others'] (plural ā category possession, excludes listener)
w-aa-maatou.exampleTranslation: Where is our food? (The food belonging to me and 2+ others, not including the listener).
w-aa-maatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'mātou' which is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitini (plural first person exclusive pronoun).

w-aa-maaua.english: our [mine and someone else's] (plural ā category possession, excludes listener)
w-aa-maaua.note: This is an [[ref|'a' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'māua' which is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takirua (dual first person exclusive pronoun).

w-aa-raatou.english: their [referring to three or more people] (plural ā category possession)
w-aa-raatou.exampleTranslation: Where are their dogs? (The dogs belonging to those three or more people).
w-aa-raatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'rātou' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitini (plural third person pronoun).

w-aa-raaua.english: their [referring to two people] (plural ā category possession)
w-aa-raaua.exampleTranslation: Where are their dogs? (The dogs belonging to those two.)
w-aa-raaua.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'rāua' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takirua (dual third person pronoun).

w-aa-taatou.english: our [mine and two or more others'] (plural ā category possession, includes listener)
w-aa-taatou.exampleTranslation: Where are our nephews? (The nephews of me and 2+ others, including the listener).
w-aa-taatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'tātou' which is the tūkapi kauawhi kiritūnei takitini (plural first person inclusive pronoun).

w-aa-taaua.english: our [mine and yours] (plural ā category possession, includes listener)
w-aa-taaua.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'tāua' which is the tūkapi kauawhi kiritūnei takirua (dual first person inclusive pronoun).

w-aahei.english: to be able, to be allowed
w-aahei.example: Ka āhei koe ki te haere.

w-aahuatanga.example: He āhuatanga o te ao Māori tēnei.
w-aahuatanga.exampleTranslation: This is a characteristic of the Māori world.

w-aakau.example: Ka ruha te kupenga, ka pae kei te ākau.
w-aakau.exampleTranslation: When the old net is worn out, it is thrown away on the shore.

w-aakonga.example: He ākonga ahau i te kura.
w-aakonga.exampleTranslation: I am a student at the school.

w-aaku.note: This is an [[ref|'a' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'au' which is the tūkapi kiritūnei takitahi (singular first person pronoun).

w-aana.note: This is an [[ref|'a' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'ia' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitahi (singular third person pronoun).

w-aanaa.note: Sometimes 'anā' is used instead. Refer to [[ref|Ānei, ānā, arā|aanei-aanaa-aaraa]] for more detail.

w-aanei.note: Sometimes "anei" is used instead. Refer to [[ref|Ānei, ānā, arā|aanei-aanaa-aaraa]] for more detail.

w-aarahi.example: Ko te ahurei o te tamaiti ka ārahi i ā tātou mahi.
w-aarahi.exampleTranslation: Let the uniqueness of the child guide our work.

w-aarai.english:
1) curtain
2) to screen off
3) to block, obstruct or prevent
w-aarai.note: Refers to something that blocks or prevents. For example, one term for sunblock is "ārai tīkākā" while immunity is "ārai mate" where "mate" is sickness.

w-aatea.exampleTranslation: The meeting is in the open space.
w-aatea.note: Refers to open areas or, in modern usage, outer space. The marae ātea is the open area in front of the wharenui on a marae.

w-aau.note: This is an [[ref|'a' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'koe' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitahi (singular second person pronoun).

w-aawhina.example: Kei te āwhina ngā tamariki i ō rātou mātua.
w-aawhina.exampleTranslation: The children are helping their parents.

w-aha.note: An [[ref|interrogative word|tupatai]], used to ask questions about things.

w-ahakoa.example: Ahakoa te ua, i haere tonu mātou.
w-ahakoa.exampleTranslation: Despite the rain, we still went.
w-ahakoa.note: Used to express contrast or concession.

w-ahatia.exampleTranslation: What can be done? So what? (An idiom to express a lack of interest in a topic).

w-ahau.note: This is one form of the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitahi (singular first person exclusive [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori. It's almost identical to au, except that where you would say "a au" you instead omit the "a" and just use "ahau".

w-ahiahi.example: I te ahiahi ka hoki mai ia.
w-ahiahi.exampleTranslation: In the afternoon she came back.
w-ahiahi.note: Also used as the verb to describe the setting of the sun.

w-aho.english:
1) string, fishing line
2) to shine, radiant light

w-ahu.english:
1) to nurture, to look after
2) to heap up
3) to move in a certain direction

w-ai.english: verbal particle with a range of uses
w-ai.note: The verbal particle "[[ref|a"|ai]]" has a range of different uses.

w-aihikiriimi.example: He pai ki ahau te aihikirīmi.

w-aituaa.english:
1) disaster, accident, mishap
2) to suffer an accident or disaster

w-ake.note:
Has multiple meanings including direction (upwards), comparison, and future time.

See [[ref|ake|ake]].

w-ako.example: Kei te ako ia i te reo Māori.
w-ako.exampleTranslation: She is learning the Māori language.
w-ako.note: Can mean both learning and teaching.

w-aku.note: This is a neutral [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'au' which is the tūkapi kiritūnei takitahi (singular first person pronoun).

w-ana.exampleTranslation: Where are their keys? (Talking about one person).
w-ana.note: This is a neutral [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'ia' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitahi (singular third person pronoun).

w-ana2.note: Multiple uses. A verbal particle which marks continuing action.

w-anake.note: Used to indicate exclusivity or limitation.

w-anga.english:
1) to face or move (in a particular direction)
2) shell, skeleton, structure, framework
w-anga.example: Inā kei te mōhio koe ko wai koe, i anga mai koe i hea, kei te mōhio koe, kei te anga atu ki hea.
w-anga.exampleTranslation: If you know who you are and where you are from, then you will know where you are going.

w-anoo.note: Has various meanings including repetition or addition. See [[ref|anō|anoo]].

w-ao.exampleTranslation: The Māori world (used to encompass the Māori worldview including culture, language, protocols and customs).

w-ara.example: Ka hikōi au i te ara roa.
w-ara.exampleTranslation: I am going to walk the long path.

w-araa.note:
Indicates something at a distance from both speaker and listener.

See [[ref|ānei, ānā, arā|aanei-aanaa-aaraa]].

w-ariki.example: Ko ia te ariki o te iwi.
w-ariki.exampleTranslation: He is the chief of the tribe.
w-ariki.note: A person of high rank or leadership. In karakia "Ariki" often refers to "the Lord" or God,

w-aroha.exampleTranslation: Love and compassion received, love and compassion given.

w-ata.example: I te ata, ka haere au ki te kura.
w-ata.exampleTranslation: In the morning I will go to school.

w-atawhai.english:
1) to show kindness, care for
2) kind

w-atu.note:
Directional particle indicating movement away from the speaker.

See [[ref|atu|atu]].

w-atua.example: Ko te mihi tuatahi ki nga atua.
w-atua.exampleTranslation: The first acknowledge is to the gods.
w-atua.note: A supernatural being or deity in Māori tradition.

w-au.note: This is one form of the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitahi (singular first person exclusive [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori. An alternative form of it is "ahau".

w-aua.english:
1) I don't know
2) those (referring to something previously mentioned in context - plural of taua)
w-aua.exampleTranslation: What is that? I don't know!
w-aua.note: Depending on intonation can also communicate "who cares?"

w-auahi.example: Kia rongo koe i te pūoho auahi.

w-awatea.example: Ka haere tātou i te awatea.
w-awatea.exampleTranslation: We will go in the daylight.

w-awhi.example: Ka awhi te whaea i tana pēpi
w-awhi.exampleTranslation: The mother will embrace her baby.

w-e.english:
1) verbal particle
2) marks short verbs as commands
2) vocative (used before name to address someone)
3) by (marks agent in passive sentences)

w-eeraa.english: those (distant from both speaker and listener)

w-eetehi.example: Kei te hiahia ahau ki ētehi āporo.

w-ehara.english:
1) not, negative marker
  2) sure enough, for sure
w-ehara.note: Used to negate nominal sentences (sentences with nouns as predicates). See [[ref|whakakāhoretanga|whakakahoretanga]] (negation).

w-eke.english:
1) to climb up on
2) to embark
w-eke.example: Ka eke ia ki runga i te pahi.
w-eke.exampleTranslation: She will get onto the bus.
w-eke.note: Used for mounting, embarking, boarding. Often combined with other words such as eke ngaru (surf), eke paihikara (cycle) and eke hōiho (horse riding).

w-engari.example: Kei te ngenge ahau, engari ka haere tonu.
w-engari.exampleTranslation: I am tired, but I will continue on.

w-haa.example: Hā ki roto. Hā ki waho.

w-haaereere.example: Kei te hāereere rātou i te ngahere.
w-haaereere.exampleTranslation: They are wandering in the forest.

w-haakari.example: Nō muri i te hui, ka tū te hākari.
w-haakari.exampleTranslation: After the meeting, a feast was held.

w-haakinakina.example: He pai ki a au ngā momo hākinakina katoa.
w-haakinakina.exampleTranslation: I like all types of sports.

w-haamama.english:
1) to shout, open the mouth
2) open, gaping
w-haamama.example: Ki te kore koe e whakarongo mai, ka hāmama tōku waha.
w-haamama.exampleTranslation: If you don't listen, I will shout.
w-haamama.note: With verbs for shouting, the doer isn't the person, it's the mouth.

w-haangai.example: I tū hāngai te whare ki te moana.
w-haangai.exampleTranslation: The house stood directly facing the sea.

w-haangi.english: earth oven, food cooked in earth oven
w-haangi.example: Ka timata te hāngi āpōpō i te ata.
w-haangi.exampleTranslation: The hāngi will start tomorrow morning.

w-haaora.example: Ka hoki mai au i te rua hāora.
w-haaora.exampleTranslation: I will return in two hours.

w-haaparangi.note: With verbs for shouting, the doer isn't the person, it's the mouth.

w-haaunga.example: I tae mai te katoa ki te hui, hāunga ko Mere.
w-haaunga.exampleTranslation: Everyone came to the meeting, except for Mere

w-haawhe.example: Homai te hāwhe o te keke.
w-haawhe.exampleTranslation: Give me half of the cake.

w-hai.english: for, to be used as (variant of "hei")

w-haka.example: He kaha te haka a te toa rā.
w-haka.exampleTranslation: The haka of that warrior is strong/powerful.

w-haki.example: Kei te kapakapa mai te haki i te hau.
w-haki.exampleTranslation: The flag is fluttering in the wind.
w-haki.note: Derived from "Jack" - an abbreviation of "Union Jack".

w-hangaia.english:
to build, construct (passive form)

make, prepare, create
w-hangaia.example: Kua hangaia e ia tētahi whare hou.
w-hangaia.exampleTranslation: He has built a new house.

w-hangarau.example: He tino whakahirahira te hangarau hou.
w-hangarau.exampleTranslation: The new technology is very important.

w-hao.english: to gather, to catch (as in fishing)
w-hao.example: Kei te hao ika a Hemi.

w-hara.english:
1) to make a mistake, transgress
2) mistake, sin
w-hara.example: E mea ana ahau kia kaua e hara toku māngai.
w-hara.exampleTranslation: I affirm that my mouth shall not transgress. (I will not sin with my words). - Psalms 17:3

w-harakeke.example: He kaha ngā muka o te harakeke.
w-harakeke.exampleTranslation: The fibres of the flax are strong.

w-hari.english:
1) to carry, take
2) to feel happy
w-hari.example: Mā wai e hari ēnei pukapuka ki te whare pukapuka?
w-hari.exampleTranslation: Who will take/carry these books to the library?

w-haria.exampleTranslation: It has been carried by her.

w-harikoa.example: He harikoa au i tēnei rā.

w-hau.example: He kaha te hau i tēnei rā.

w-haurua.example: Homai te haurua o te keke.
w-haurua.exampleTranslation: Give me half of the cake.

w-hea.note: [[ref|Interrogative word|tupatai]] used to ask about location.

w-heeoi.example: I hiahia ia ki te haere ki te takutai, hēoi ka timata te ua.
w-heeoi.exampleTranslation: She wanted to go to the beach, however it started to rain.

w-hei.english: for, at, as a means of, preposition marking future time or location

w-hemo.english: to be dead, pass by, be gone

w-here.example: Kia here koe i ōu hū.

w-herea.exampleTranslation: Is this a canoe that can be tied up? (A whakatauaki about the inevitability of death.)
w-herea.note: Passive form of 'here' (to tie). Here + passive suffix -a.

w-hia.note: [[ref|Interrogative word|tupatai]] used to ask about quantity.

w-hiahia.example: Kei te hiahia au ki te kai.

w-hii.example: I haere mātou ki te hī ika.

w-hiikoi.english: to walk, to step, to march
w-hiikoi.example: I hīkoi mātou ki te marae.

w-hika.example: E hika mā! Kua tō te rā.
w-hika.note: A term of address to people of any gender, commonly used in eastern dialects. It can also be used as an exclamation of surprise (e.g., 'E hika!').

w-hiki.english:
1) to lift up, raise,
2) to carry in arms, to nurse
w-hiki.example: Kaua e hiki tēnā, he wera rawa!
w-hiki.exampleTranslation: Don't lift that, it's too hot!

w-hine.english: term of address for a girl
w-hine.example: E hine, kei te pēhea koe?
w-hine.note: Used when addressing a young female.

w-hinga.english: to fall from an upright position
w-hinga.example: Ki te kore he pakiaka, ka hinga te rākau.
w-hinga.exampleTranslation: Without roots, the tree will fall.

w-hinu.example: Ka kitea a Matariki, ka wera te hinu.
w-hinu.exampleTranslation: When Matariki is seen, the fat is heated.

w-hipi.example: He nui ngā hipi i te pāmu.
w-hipi.exampleTranslation: There are many sheep on the farm.

w-hoa.example: Kei te haere au ki te whare o tōku hoa.
w-hoa.exampleTranslation: I am going to my friend's house.
w-hoa.note: Any word derived from "hoa" is in the [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]]. This includes hoariri (enemy).

w-hoariri.note: Any word derived from "hoa" is in the [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]].

w-hoatu.example: Hoatu te pukapuka ki a ia.
w-hoatu.note: Directional verb indicating giving away from the speaker (compare with 'homai').

w-hoe.example: Kei te hoe rātou i te waka.

w-hoki.english:
1) to return
2) also, too, as well
w-hoki.note: Has two main meanings: as a verb 'to return' and as a particle meaning 'also/too'. For its use as a particle, see [[ref|hoki|hoki]].

w-hokohoko.example: Kei te hokohoko ia ki te toa.
w-hokohoko.exampleTranslation: She is shopping at the store.

w-hokona.exampleTranslation: It will be bought by me.
w-hokona.note: Passive form of 'hoko' (to buy/sell). hoko + passive suffix -na

w-hono.example: Ka hono ngā awa e rua.

w-hoohaa.example: Kei te hōhā au ki a ia.

w-hoohonu.note: Describes significant depth, physically or metaphorically.

w-hooia.example: He hōia ia i te pakanga.
w-hooia.exampleTranslation: He was a soldier in the war.

w-hoomai.note: Directional verb indicating giving toward the speaker.

w-hopu.example: Ka hopu te ngeru i te kiore.

w-horo.english:
1) to fall down, crumble, slip
2) quick

w-hua.example: Kei te kai hua rākau au.

w-huarahi.note: Refers to both literal roads and figurative paths or methods.

w-huia.note: A culturally significant bird in te ao Māori.

w-huka.example: He nui rawa te huka i roto i tēnei inu.
w-huka.exampleTranslation: There is too much sugar in this drink.

w-hunga.example: He hunga kaha rātou ki te mahi.
w-hunga.exampleTranslation: They are a group of strong workers.

w-huri.note: Describes rotation, changing direction, or transformation.

w-hurihuri.english: to turn around and around, repeatedly

w-huruhuru.example: He ao te rangi ka uhia a ma te huruhuru te manu ka rere ai.
w-huruhuru.exampleTranslation: It requires clouds to clothe heaven and feathers to make a bird fly.
w-huruhuru.note: In Kāi Tahu dialect, this includes hair on the head.

w-i.english: past tense marker, object marker, from
w-i.example: I haere au ki te kura.
w-i.note: Has multiple grammatical functions depending on context, including communicating past tense or indicating the direct object of a verbal sentence.

w-i-naaianei.example: Kei te mahi ahau i nāianei.

w-ia.note: This is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitahi (singular third person [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori. It does not communicate any information about gender, unlike he/she in English.

w-iho.note: Directional particle indicating downward movement. See [[ref|iho|iho]]

w-ika.example: Kei te haere au ki te hī ika.

w-ina.example: Ina tae mai koe, ka haere tāua.
w-ina.exampleTranslation: When you arrive, we will go.

w-inaa.example: Inā te pai o te kai!
w-inaa.note: Used for emphasis or to draw attention

w-ine.example: Kei te ine ia i te roa o te rūma.
w-ine.exampleTranslation: He is measuring the length of the room.

w-ingoa.note: Used for personal names, place names, and names of things.

w-ira.english:
1) dot, spot, decimal point
2) gene, particle
w-ira.example: He kākahu whero me ngā ira pango.
w-ira.exampleTranslation: It's a red dress with black dots.

w-irirangi.example: Kei te whakarongo ahau ki te reo irirangi.
w-irirangi.exampleTranslation: I am listening to the radio.

w-ka.note: Verbal particle with a range of meanings, see [[ref|ka|ka]].

w-kaahore.note: The main negative marker for verbal sentences. A variation of {{kāore}}.

w-kaainga.example: Kei te haere au ki te kāinga.

w-kaao.example: Kāo, kāore au e haere ana.

w-kaaore.english: not - negative used for verb sentences
w-kaaore.example: Kāore rātou i tae mai ki te hui.
w-kaaore.exampleTranslation: They did not come to the meeting.

w-kaapene.example: Ko wai te kāpene o te waka?
w-kaapene.exampleTranslation: Who is the captain of the ship?

w-kaare.example: Kāre au e mōhio ki hea ka tīmata.
w-kaare.exampleTranslation: I don't know where to start

w-kaareti.example: He pai ki te rāpeti te kai kāreti.

w-kaatahi.example: Ka kai ia, kātahi ka moe.

w-kaati.english: stop, cease (as an interjection or negative command)

w-kaawana.example: He kaupapa tēnei nā te kāwana.

w-kaawanatanga.example: He rerekē ngā momo kāwanatanga huri noa i te ao.
w-kaawanatanga.exampleTranslation: There are different types of government around the world.

w-kaawhe.example: He kāwhe hou tēnei i te pāmu.
w-kaawhe.exampleTranslation: This is a new calf on the farm.

w-kahurangi.english:
1) blue
2) person (usually a woman) of high status or rank

w-kai-1.english: (particle) at, on, in (of present position or time)

w-kaimoana.example: He pai ki a au te kaimoana.

w-kainga.example: I kainga ngā pihikete e ngā tamariki.
w-kainga.exampleTranslation: The biscuits were eaten by the children.

w-kaitiaki.example: Ko wai te kaitiaki o te whenua?
w-kaitiaki.exampleTranslation: Who is the caretaker of the land?

w-kakau.example: Kua pakaru te kakau o te pāraha.
w-kakau.exampleTranslation: The handle of the tool is broken.

w-kake.example: Ka kake ia ki te maunga.

w-kamo.example: Waiwai ana te roimata ki ōku kamo
w-kamo.exampleTranslation: Tears are welling up in my eyes.

w-kano.example: He aha te kano o tō kākahu?
w-kano.exampleTranslation: What is the color of your clothes?

w-kapu.exampleTranslation: Would you like a cup of coffee?

w-kapua.exampleTranslation: There are a lot of clouds.

w-kara.example: He aha te kara o tō kākahu?
w-kara.exampleTranslation: What is the color of your clothes?

w-karaka.note: Also the name of a native tree with orange berries

w-karanga.example: Ka karanga mai ia ki ahau.

w-karani.example: He tino mohio tōku karani ki te raranga.
w-karani.exampleTranslation: My granny is very skilled at weaving.

w-kararehe.exampleTranslation: The horse is a big animal.

w-kare.english:
1) dear - a term of address
2) ripple
3) stove, heater
w-kare.example: E kare, kei te pēhea koe?

w-karere.example: I tae mai te karere me te kōrero nui.
w-karere.exampleTranslation: The messenger arrived with important news.

w-kata.example: He kotahi nā Tūhoe ka kata te pō
w-kata.exampleTranslation: Even with only one Tūhoe, the night laughs (a whakatauaki).

w-katakata.example: Ko te katakata te rongoā pai rawa atu.

w-katoa.example: I kite ahau i ngā manu katoa.

w-kau.english:
1) manner particle with various meanings including solitarily, unreservedly, exclusively
2) cow
3) to swim
w-kau.example: Kāore kau he kai i roto i te puku
w-kau.exampleTranslation: There is no food in the stomach.

w-kauhoe.example: Me ako koe ki te kauhoe.

w-kaukau.example: He pai ki te kaukau i te ata.
w-kaukau.exampleTranslation: It's nice to bathe in the morning.

w-kaumaatua.example: Kei te noho ngā kaumātua i runga i te paepae.
w-kaumaatua.exampleTranslation: The elders are sitting on the speakers' bench.

w-kaupapa.example: He aha te kaupapa o te hui?
w-kaupapa.exampleTranslation: What is the topic/agenda of the meeting?

w-kaute.example: Kei te kaute ahau i aku moni.

w-kauwhata.example: Tirohia tēnei kauwhata e whakaatu ana i ngā hoko.
w-kauwhata.exampleTranslation: Look at this graph that shows the sales.

w-kawe.example: Kei te kawe ahau i ngā pukapuka.

w-kawenga.example: He taimaha rawa tēnei kawenga māku.
w-kawenga.exampleTranslation: This load is too heavy for me.

w-keehua.example: He pai ki ngā tamariki ngā pūrākau kēhua.

w-keemu.example: He aha te ingoa o tēnei kēmu?
w-keemu.exampleTranslation: What is the name of this game?

w-kei.english:
1) present time and location preposition
2) verbal particle for continuing present/future action

w-keke.example: Kei te kai au i te keke.

w-kekeno.example: Kei te takoto te kekeno i runga i ngā kōhatu.
w-kekeno.exampleTranslation: The seal is lying on the rocks.

w-ki.note: A particle with a variety of different meanings, generally focused on motion towards something.

w-kia.english:
1) used to suggest something should be
2) used to say how many things are needed
3) used to indicate purpose
w-kia.note: A particle with a wide range of uses.

w-kii.example: He aha tāu i kī mai?

w-kiihai.example: Kīhai au i haere ki te hui.
w-kiihai.exampleTranslation: I did not go to the meeting.

w-kiiia.example: He aha te kupu i kīia?
w-kiiia.exampleTranslation: What was the word that was said?

w-kikorangi.example: He kikorangi rawa te rangi i tēnei rā.
w-kikorangi.exampleTranslation: The sky is very blue today.

w-kimi.example: Kei te kimi ahau i aku kī.
w-kimi.exampleTranslation: I am looking for my keys.

w-kimihia.english: be sought, be looked for, be searched for
w-kimihia.example: Kimihia te huarahi e tika ana māu.
w-kimihia.exampleTranslation: Seek the path that's right for you.

w-kiore.example: He kai te kiore mā te kāhu.
w-kiore.exampleTranslation: The rat is food for the hawk.

w-kiri.example: Me tiaki koe i tō kiri.
w-kiri.exampleTranslation: You should look after your skin.

w-kirikiri.example: He maha ngā kōhatu iti i te kirikiri.
w-kirikiri.exampleTranslation: There are many small stones in the sand.

w-kiromita.example: E rima kiromita te tawhiti o te kura.
w-kiromita.exampleTranslation: The school is five kilometres away.

w-kite.example: Kua kite au i tō hū ki raro i te moenga.
w-kite.exampleTranslation: I found your shoe under the bed.

w-kitea.english: be seen, be found, be discovered
w-kitea.example: Kua kitea te kī i ngaro.
w-kitea.exampleTranslation: The key that was lost has been found.

w-kitenga.example: Nō taku kitenga i a ia, ka koa ahau.
w-kitenga.exampleTranslation: Upon my seeing him, I was happy.

w-kiwi.exampleTranslation: The kiwi is a nocturnal bird.

w-ko.english: A particle with a number of uses including identifying or specifying a subject

w-koa.english:
1) be happy, glad, joyful, pleasant
2) please
3) indeed, used to add emphasis
w-koa.example: Tēnā koe, homai te pukapuka na, koa.
w-koa.exampleTranslation: My heart is happy because of your arrival.

w-koe.note: This is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitahi (singular second person [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]).

w-kongakonga.english:
1) to be crumbled into fragments
2) small piece, fragment, chip

w-koo.english: at a distance, yonder, over there
w-koo.example: Kei kō te kura e tū ana.
w-koo.exampleTranslation: The school is standing over there.

w-kookaa.exampleTranslation: My mother is at the marae.

w-kookiri.english:
1) to charge, rush at
2) to champion, advocate

w-koorere.english:
1) tap, faucet
2) anything that channels liquids such as funnels or pipes

w-koorerotia.english: be spoken, be said, be read, be addressed
w-koorerotia.example: Kōrerotia te pukapuka ki te tamaiti.
w-koorerotia.exampleTranslation: Read the book to the child.

w-koorua.note: This is the tūkapi kiritūnā takirua (dual second person [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]])

w-koowhai.example: He kōwhai ngā puāwai o te rākau kōwhai.
w-koowhai.exampleTranslation: The flowers of the kōwhai tree are yellow.

w-koro.english: Term of address for an elderly man, grandfather.

w-koroua.english:
1) to be old
2) elderly man, grandfather
w-koroua.example: Kua koroua haere taku matua kēkē.

w-koutou.note: This is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitini (plural second person [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]).

w-kua.english: A verbal particle indicating completed action or that something has changed state.

w-kui.english: Term of address for an elderly woman.

w-kuia.exampleTranslation: My grandmother is a wise woman.

w-kukume.note: Usually kūmea in the passive form.

w-maa.english:
1) white
2) clean
3) particle used to indicate future possession
4) particle used to indicate who will perform the action (actor emphatic)
5) by means of, via
5) particle used after nouns to mean "and others"

w-maahau.exampleTranslation: This cup of tea is for you.

w-maaku.note: Indicates future action by the speaker or allocation to the speaker.

w-maana.note: Indicates future action by a third person or allocation to them.

w-maaori.example: Ko te reo Māori te reo tuatahi o Aotearoa.
w-maaori.exampleTranslation: The Māori language is the first language of New Zealand.
w-maaori.note: Refers to the indigenous people of Aotearoa/New Zealand and their language and culture.

w-maaroo.note: Describes physical hardness or firmness of character.

w-maatakitaki.example: Kei te mātakitaki mātou i te pouaka whakaata.

w-maatau.english:
1) to know, understand
2) we, us (variant of mātou, the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitini (plural first person exclusive [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]))

w-maatou.english: we, us (three or more, excluding addressee)
w-maatou.example: Kei te haere mātou ki te kura.
w-maatou.note: This is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitini (plural first person exclusive [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori.

w-maatua.example: Kei te tautoko ō mātua i a koe.

w-maaua.example: Ka haere māua ki te tāone.
w-maaua.exampleTranslation: We (two of us) are going to town.
w-maaua.note: This is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takirua (dual first person exclusive [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori.

w-maha.example: He maha ngā pukapuka i runga i te tēpu.
w-maha.exampleTranslation: There are many books on the table.

w-mahara.example: Kei te mahara au ki a ia.

w-mahia.english: be done, be worked, be made, be performed

w-mai.note:
Directional particle indicating movement toward the speaker.

See [[ref|mai|mai]].

w-makawe.note: Used in plural unless referring to a single strand.

w-makere.english:
1) to be dropped
2) to come/take off

w-mana.note: A key cultural concept referring to spiritual power, authority, and prestige.

w-manaaki.english: to support, take care of, show hospitality to
w-manaaki.note: A core cultural value of caring for others and upholding their mana.

w-manawa.example: Ka aroha tōku manawa ki a ia.
w-manawa.exampleTranslation: My heart feels compassion for him/her.

w-manuhiri.example: I tae mai ngā manuhiri i te ata.
w-manuhiri.exampleTranslation: The guests arrived in the morning.

w-marae.english: courtyard (shortened form of marae ātea), typically used to include the complex of buildings around the marae
w-marae.example: Kei te hui mātou ki te marae.
w-marae.exampleTranslation: We are meeting at the marae.
w-marae.note: The traditional communal meeting place, a focal point for Māori communities.

w-marama.example: Kua tae mai te marama hou.
w-marama.note: Refers to both the moon and a month (lunar cycle).

w-maramara.example: Horoia ngā maramara i te tēpu.
w-maramara.exampleTranslation: Clean the crumbs from the table.

w-marangai.note: Has meanings related to north/east and winds from those directions.

w-mata.example: Whakahokia te reo mai i te mata o te pene, ki te mata o te arero.
w-mata.exampleTranslation: Bring the language back from the tip of the pen to the tip of the tongue.

w-mataku.example: Kei te mataku ia i te kurī.
w-mataku.exampleTranslation: He is afraid of the dog.

w-matapihi.example: Ko te reo Māori, he matapihi ki te ao Māori.
w-matapihi.exampleTranslation: The Māori language is a window to the Māori world.

w-matuu.english:
1) fat
2) chemical, material (modern)
3) gist or central point of a matter

w-mau.english:
1) to take/bring/wield
2) wear
3) to be caught/held

w-mauii.example: Kei te taha māui o te pereti te paoka.
w-mauii.exampleTranslation: The fork is on the left side of the plate.

w-maumahara.example: Kei te maumahara au ki a ia.

w-mauri.note: A common expression in te reo Māori, acknowledging the breath of life, used as a call to claim the right to speak.

w-mauria.example: Kaua e mauria tō pōtae hou.

w-me.english:
1) should (forms a weak command)
2) and (used to join nouns)
3) with

w-meatia.english: be done, be made, be said

w-meenaa.example: Kei a koe te tikanga mēnā kei te hiahia koe ki te heri mai i tētahi māngai.
w-meenaa.exampleTranslation: It is up to you if you want to bring a representative.

w-mehemea.example: Mehemea ka ua, kāore au e haere.
w-mehemea.exampleTranslation: If it rains, I won't go.

w-meneti.example: E rima meneti e toe ana.

w-mihi.example: Ka mihi ahau ki a koe.

w-moana.example: Kei te rere te waka i te moana.
w-moana.exampleTranslation: The boat is sailing on the sea.

w-moko.english:
1) Lizard
2) Traditional tattoo
3) Term of address to a grandchild: E moko.

w-momo.example: He aha te momo rākau tēnei?
w-momo.exampleTranslation: What kind of tree is this?
w-momo.note: Used to classify or categorize things.

w-motu.english:
1) island
2) to cut, cut off, sever

w-motuhake.english:
1) to separated, set side
2) separated, distinct, special

w-mua.note: A [[ref|locative noun|tuwahi]] used to indicate position (front) or time (before).

w-mura.english:
1) be aflame, on fire
2) blaze, flame

w-muri.note: A [[ref|locative noun|muri]] used to indicate position (behind) or time (after).

w-mutu.example: Kua mutu te kai i a koe?
w-mutu.note: Does not necessarily indicate completion. The kupu "oti" is preferred if something is complete.

w-naa.note: Indicates possession or agency, often in questions about ownership.[[ref|'Ā' category possessive|a-o-categories]].

w-naaianei.note: Marks the present moment in time. Typically prefixed with i-, nō- or o-.

w-naaku.note: Indicates ownership or agency. [[ref|'Ā' category possessive|a-o-categories]], singular form.

w-naana.note: Indicates ownership or agency by a third person. [[ref|'Ā' category possessive|a-o-categories]], singular form.

w-naawai.english: presently, in due course, after a while

w-nau.note: Often used in greetings and welcomes.

w-nee.note: Used at the end of sentences to seek confirmation, similar to 'eh?' or 'right?"

w-ngaa.note: The plural form of 'te', the [[ref|pū tautuhi|pumau]] or definite article - used before plural nouns.

w-ngaakau.note: Refers to the emotional or spiritual heart, not the physical organ.

w-ngahere.exampleTranslation: The birds are in the forest.

w-noho.english:
1) to sit
2) to stay
3) to live
w-noho.example: Kei te noho ia ki Tāmaki Makaurau.

w-noo.note: Used for origin or possession in the[[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]].

w-noona.note: Indicates third person ownership in the [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]].

w-o.example: Ko te ingoa o te tamaiti.
w-o.note: This particle is used to introduce possessive comments for [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]] relationships.

w-oo.english:
1) your (neutral plural possessive)
2) belonging to (o category possessive determiner)
w-oo.note: This particle can either be the neutral [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun) which is one of the possessive forms of 'koe' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitahi (singular second person pronoun), or it can form an [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]] possessive [[ref|determiner|pumau]] such as in "Ko tēnei ō mātou whare" (These are our houses). This is a .

w-oo-koorua.english: your [speaking to two people] (plural ō category possession)
w-oo-koorua.exampleTranslation: Where are your houses? (The houses belonging to you two.)
w-oo-koorua.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'kōrua' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takirua (dual second person pronoun).

w-oo-koutou.english: your [speaking to three or more people] (plural ō category possession)
w-oo-koutou.exampleTranslation: Where are your parents? (The parents of you three or more people).
w-oo-koutou.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'koutou' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitini (plural second person pronoun).

w-oo-maatou.english: our [mine and two or more others'] (plural ō category possession, excludes listener)
w-oo-maatou.exampleTranslation: Where are our rooms? (The rooms belonging to me and 2+ others, not including the listener).
w-oo-maatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'mātou' which is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitini (plural first person exclusive pronoun).

w-oo-maaua.english: our [mine and someone else's] (plural ō category possession, excludes listener)
w-oo-maaua.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'māua' which is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takirua (dual first person exclusive pronoun).

w-oo-raatou.english: their [referring to three or more people] (plural ō category possession)
w-oo-raatou.exampleTranslation: Where are their cars? (The cars belonging to those three or more people).
w-oo-raatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'rātou' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitini (plural third person pronoun).

w-oo-raaua.english: their [referring to two people] (plural ō category possession)
w-oo-raaua.exampleTranslation: Where are their houses? (The houses belonging to those two.)
w-oo-raaua.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'rāua' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takirua (dual third person pronoun).

w-oo-taatou.english: our [mine and two or more others'] (plural ō category possession, includes listener)
w-oo-taatou.exampleTranslation: Where are our parents? (The parents of me and 2+ others, including the listener).
w-oo-taatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'tātou' which is the tūkapi kauawhi kiritūnei takitini (plural first person inclusive pronoun).

w-oo-taaua.english: our [mine and yours] (plural ō category possession, includes listener)
w-oo-taaua.note: This is an [[ref|'ō' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'tāua' which is the tūkapi kauawhi kiritūnei takirua (dual first person inclusive pronoun).

w-ooku.note: This is an [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'au' which is the tūkapi kiritūnei takitahi (singular first person pronoun).

w-oona.note: This is an [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'ia' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitahi (singular third person pronoun).

w-oorite.english: to be identical, to be equal

w-oou.note: This is an [[ref|'o' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitini (plural possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'koe' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitahi (singular second person pronoun).

w-ope.english: brigade, troop, group of people moving together

w-paa.english:
1) to touch, to affect
2) a fortified settlement
3) a term of address for father or older male (e pā)

w-paahi.english:
1) to pass, to enact
2) purse, wallet

w-paatiki.note: A general term for flounder-type fish.

w-pae.english:
1) shelf, horizon, anything horizontal
2) to lay horizontally
3) to be cast ashore
4) circumference

w-paepae.english:
1) container
2) speakers’ bench on the marae

w-papa.exampleTranslation: Your pen is on the floor.

w-pare.english:
1) to turn aside, ward off
2) headband, garland

w-pau.english: to be consumed, used up completely, all gone

w-pito.english:
1) end, extremity
2) pole (of a magnet)
3) belly button

w-poi.english: a light ball on a string, swung rhythmically to accompany singing

w-poro.english: to cut off, to cut short

w-punua.note: A foal is a punua hōiho. A piglet is a punua poaka.

w-pupuhi.english:
1) to swell, expand
2) to shoot, blow, spout (as a whale)

w-puru.english:
1) to block up, plug
2) to put, place somewhere

w-puu.english:
1) letter of the alphabet
2) gun
3) to blow gently

w-raa.note: Has multiple uses including as one of the [[ref|positional particles|puhea]].

w-raakau.example: He maha ngā rākau i te ngahere.
w-raakau.exampleTranslation: There are many trees in the forest.

w-raanei.note: Used to present alternatives, typically follows the second phrase or word.

w-raarangi.example: Rarangi maunga tu tonu, tu tonu; rarangi tangata ngaro noa, ngaro noa.
w-raarangi.exampleTranslation: A mountain range (line of mountains) stands for eternity but a line of people just disappears.

w-raatou.example: Kei te haere rātou ki te kura.
w-raatou.note: This is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitini (plural third person [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori.

w-raaua.note: This is the tūkapi kiritūrā takirua (dual third person [[ref|pronoun|tukapi]]) in te reo Māori.

w-raki.english:
1) north
2) to be dried up, dehydrated

w-rangatira.example: Ko ia te rangatira o te iwi.
w-rangatira.exampleTranslation: He is the leader of the tribe.

w-raro.note: A [[ref||locative noun|tuwahi]] indicating position below something else.

w-rau.english:
1) leaf
2) hundred
3) to put into, gather into
w-rau.example: He rau tāngata i te hui.
w-rau.exampleTranslation: There were a hundred people at the meeting.

w-rere.english:
1) to fly,
2) to flow
3) to sail
4) to escape

w-riro.english: to be taken, obtained, carried away

w-rongo.example: Kei te rongo au i te waiata.

w-roo.note:
Shortened form of "roto i te/ngā" in eastern dialect.
See [[ref|locative nouns|tuwahi]].

w-taa.english:
1) Used to indicate [[ref|'a' category|a-o-categories]] possession of something singular - to form [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] such as tā mātou.
2) to draw/paint/publish/print
3) according to, as said by

w-taa-koorua.english: your [speaking to two people] (singular ā category possession)
w-taa-koorua.exampleTranslation: Where is your book? (The book belonging to you two.)
w-taa-koorua.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'kōrua' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takirua (dual second person pronoun).

w-taa-koutou.english: your [speaking to three or more people] (singular ā category possession)
w-taa-koutou.exampleTranslation: Where is your dog? (The dog belonging to you three or more people).
w-taa-koutou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'koutou' which is the tūkapi kiritūnā takitini (plural second person pronoun).

w-taa-maatou.english: our [mine and two or more others'] (singular ā category possession, excludes listener)
w-taa-maatou.exampleTranslation: Where is our computer? (The computer belonging to me and 2+ others, not including the listener).
w-taa-maatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'mātou' which is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takitini (plural first person exclusive pronoun).

w-taa-maaua.english: our [mine and someone else's] (singular ā category possession, excludes listener)
w-taa-maaua.note: This is an [[ref|'a' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'māua' which is the tūkapi kaupare kiritūnei takirua (dual first person exclusive pronoun).

w-taa-raatou.english: their [referring to three or more people] (singular ā category possession)
w-taa-raatou.exampleTranslation: Where is their dog? (The dog belonging to those three or more people).
w-taa-raatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'rātou' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takitini (plural third person pronoun).

w-taa-raaua.english: their [referring to two people] (singular ā category possession)
w-taa-raaua.exampleTranslation: Where is their dog? (The dog belonging to those two.)
w-taa-raaua.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'rāua' which is the tūkapi kiritūrā takirua (dual third person pronoun).

w-taa-taatou.english: our [mine and two or more others'] (singular ā category possession, includes listener)
w-taa-taatou.exampleTranslation: Where is our nephew? (The nephew of me and 2+ others, including the listener).
w-taa-taatou.note: This is an [[ref|'ā' category|a-o-categories]] [[ref|tūkapi riro|tukapi-riro]] takitahi (singular possessive pronoun). It is one of the possessive forms of 'tātou' which is the tūkapi kauawhi kiritūnei takitini (plural first person inclusive pronoun).
